If a manual `\bibitem` is passed an optional argument, then texlab does not recognize the reference and issues a false "Undefined reference" error when it is `\cite`d.

```tex
\documentclass{article}
\begin{document}
See~\cite{ref1}. % Undefined reference [11]
\begin{thebibliography}{xx}
\bibitem[xx]{ref1} Reference 1
\end{thebibliography}
\end{document}
```

The error goes away if the `[xx]` is removed.


Similar to #1171, but regards an edge case that was not dealt with in the corresponding PR #1244.

TexLab recently added the Beamer frame environment to the list of workspace symbols. However, this does not seem to be working in my setup. Others symbols such as sections and figures do appear as usual.

I'm using Texlab version 5.25.1 with Neovim. I tested in my own latex projects and the following basic Beamer presentation but nothing seems to work.
```latex
\documentclass{beamer}
\begin{document}

\section{A section}

\begin{frame}{Frame Title}
	Test frame
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Frame Title 2}
	Test frame 2
\end{frame}

\end{document}
```

Use the example below

```tex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{zref-clever}

\begin{document}

We have
\begin{equation}\label{eq1}
	A = B,
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}\label{eq2}
	B = C.
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}\label{eq3}
	C = D.
\end{equation}

We have \zcref[nocomp]{eq1,eq2,eq3} imply $A=D$.

\end{document}
```

When creating and using \newcommand with \ref, texlab doesn't consider the label referenced as used.
Example:
```
\newcommand{\reref}[1]{\ref{#1}}

\begin{document}

\reref{fig:test}

\begin{figure}
\caption{test}
\label{fig:test}
\end{figure}

\end{document}
```

The figure will receive the hint "Unused label". The same thing happens with citations (`\cite`).
